Missing Value Treatment¶

Checking for Null Values and Replacing them

In [282]:
bank_marketing_campaign_df[bank_marketing_campaign_df.isnull().any(axis=1)]
Out[282]:
age job marital education default balance housing loan contact day month duration campaign pdays previous poutcome Target
  • We can see above that there are no null values.

The following variables have unknown values:

  • Job - A very small fraction(288 out of total 45211 records) have unknown values. Hence we can simply encode it as a category using one hot encoding
  • Education - A small fraction (1857 out of total 45211 records) have unknown values. We can simply replace it with Secondary Education as over 50% records have it, so it makes it a mode value
  • Contact Communication Type - Replace contact type of unknown with Cellular. This is because a little over 57% of the record have Cellular Contact Type.
  • Outcome of previous marketing campaign -

Label Encoding¶

The following independant variables will need to be label encoded

  1. Education level
  2. default
  3. housing
  4. loan
  5. day
  6. month

The above univariate ananlysis shows that:

  • The conversion rate of the previous campaign was very very low.
  • Majority of the customers were last contacted during the middle months of the year May,June,July,August
  • The members were contacted evenly across all days of the month. No preferrence was given to Start or End Date of the month.
  • Majority of the Customers were contacted using CellPhone. A good amount of customers were unknown. So we replaced the unknowns with Cellular as CellPhone is the mode value. Also since unknown have call times, so the mode of communication could not be anything apart from Phone Calls.
  • Only 20% customers have personal loan while a little over 55% have housing loan
  • Less than 5% Customers have a Credit default.
  • Over 50% Customers have a secondary education.

The bi-variate analysis shows:

  1. Customers with Tertiary education have the highest chance of responding yes to the campaign. Those with secondary education have a little higher chance of responding yes than those with Primary education.

  2. Customers who do not have a record of credit card default has slightly higher chance of responding yes to the current
    campaign.

  3. Customers who do not have a housing loan have a higher chance of responding yes to the campaign.

  4. Customers who do not have a personal loan have a higher chance of responding yes to the campaign.

  5. Customers who were contacted with cellphone have almost similar chances of responding yes to the campaign as the customers who were contacted with landline.

  6. Customer who were last contacted on the first day of the month had the highest chance of saying a yes. Those who were contacted on 10th day of the month have the next highest chance of saying yes.

  7. Customers who were contacted on March, Sepetember, October, December have a very high chance(almost 50%) of responding yes to the campaign.

  8. Customers who responded yes to the previous campaign has the highest chance(65%) of saying yes to the current campaign

  9. Students and Retired people have the highest chance of responding yes to the campaign

We will try to explore the relationship of the Target variable with the Independant varilables that are continuos(numbers). For that we will use various JointPlots.

In [299]:
sns.pairplot(bank_marketing_campaign_df[['Target', 'age', 'balance','duration','campaign','pdays','previous']]);

The Multi Variate analysis shows:

  1. Contacting a customer more than 30 times for the current campaign had no impact in customer response.
  2. Customer who were contacted more than 30 times in the previous campaign had no impact on customer response.
  3. Call Duration had no impact on the customer response.
  4. Customers with lower balance have the chance of opening a term deposit.
  5. Age does not have any impact on Customers choice of opening a term deposit.
  6. Customers with lower bank balance were contacted more number of times for the current campaign.
  7. More time was spent on call with customers who have very low account balance.
  8. People who have just retired(60 yrs) are among the people with highest bank balance.
  9. Duration of call with customers with higher bank balance in lower. 10.A Customer who had long call duration was contacted lesser number of time. 11.Customers with age above 60 were contacted relatively lesser number of time.

In [305]:
def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Method recall
0 Logistic Regression 0.81
0 Decision Tree 0.32
0 Bagging Classifier 0.45
0 Ada Boosting 0.39
0 Random Forest 0.44

Conclusion : We will choose logistic Regression Model among all as the model has a high Recall Value of 81%.

This behavior is understandable because the dataset is imbalanced over the Target variable 'Personal Loan'. There are 480 records which has an Outcome 1 for this variable while 4520 records have an Outcome of 0. For such a case usually Recall value is a True measure of the effectiveness of the model. A very high value of recalls indicates a very low of False Negative. That means that a very low number of Cutomers who were thought to be not responding actually responded. For a campaign with such a low response, missing out of potential customers who were actually intersted might have caused Very High Oppourtunity Cost.

On the other hand it doesn't harm to have high False Negatives. In this problem the False negatives are actually more than False positives. But if we look at the percentage of total Customers who were not interested, the model only found 10% interested. So if they try to outreach them it wont be that watage of resources.

Finally the ROC AUC Score is at 90% which shows that a very true high true positive rate for false positive rate.
